04345nam a22006615i 9781442627277DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172005onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426272777 a10.3138/97814426272772doi  a(DE-B1597)483055  a(OCoLC)1004882398  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aHIS0060202bisacsh04a362.29/16/097109042221 aCarstairs, Catherine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJailed for Possession :bIllegal Drug Use, Regulation, and Power in Canada, 1920-1961 /cCatherine Carstairs. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2017] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Gender and History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. The Drug Panic of the 1920s and the Drive for Chinese Exclusion -- tChapter 2. ‘Hop Heads’: The Effects of Criminalization, 1920–1945 -- tChapter 3. ‘Hypes’: Using and Quitting, 1945–1961 -- tChapter 4. ‘After a Short Struggle’: Police Officers and Drug Users -- tChapter 5. Proscribing Prescribing: Doctors, Drug Users, and the Division of Narcotic Control -- tChapter 6. Turning Rounders into Square Johns: Drug Users and the John Howard Society -- tChapter 7. Free Drugs or Prison for Life? Changing Approaches to Treatment -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs rates of illegal drug use increase, the debates over drug policy heat up. While some believe penalties should be harsher, others advocate complete decriminalisation. Certainly, debate over the 'war on drugs' is not new. In the early 1920s, as the drive for Chinese Exclusion gathered steam, Canadians blamed the Chinese for the growing use of opium and other drugs, and parliamentarians passed extremely harsh drug laws to counter this use. These laws remained in place until the 1960s.In Jailed for Possession, Catherine Carstairs examines the impact of these drug laws on users' health, work lives, and relationships. In the middle of the century, drug users regularly went to jail for up to two years for possession of even the smallest amount of opium, morphine, heroin, or cocaine, often spending more time incarcerated than on the street. As enforcement increased and drugs became harder to obtain, drug use became an increasingly central preoccupation, making it almost impossible for users to hold down steady jobs, support families, or maintain solid relationships.Jailed for Possession is the first social history of drug use in Canada and provides a careful examination of drug users and their regulators including doctors, social workers, and police officers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDrug abusexGovernment policyzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aDrug abusexTreatmentzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aDrugs of abusexLaw and legislationxCriminal provisionsxSocial aspectszCanada. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262727740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442627277423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442627277.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK